<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="550" pageId="6" pageNumber="549" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1444,2011]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="550" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1552,1578]" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Male</emphasis>
: Body medium-sized. Antenna segments with alternate short dark bands apically. Fastigium of vertex compressed laterally, dorsally narrow, apex rounded from lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[951,1041,1588,1614]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), acute from dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1423,1588,1614]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Fastigium of vertex separated from frons by a furrow. Eyes globular (
<figureCitation box="[955,1048,1624,1650]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Pronotum saddle-shaped, longer than broad and extending posteriorly; dorsal anterior margin slightly concave (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1148,1660,1686]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); disk dorsally depressed between second and third transversal sulcus, surface with a spoon-shaped mark, the margin smooth or constricted at transverse sulcus; posterior margin broadly rounded, very slightly concaved (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1133,1732,1758]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="549">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), ventral margins of lateral lobes incline downwards, anterior angle obtuse, posterior angle rounded. Fore femora genicular lobes armed with a single spine on the inner side, outer side unarmed; middle femora genicular lobes armed with a single spine on both inner and outer side; hind femora genicular lobes armed with two spines on both inner and outer side. Fore and middle femora unarmed ventrally; hind femora ventrally armed with several small spins. Tegmina broad and long, reaching middle of middle tibiae, slightly inflated transversally (Fig. 3,4). MA veins curved upward, with 7 branches. Rs veins arised from 2/3 part of R vein. Hind wing shorter than tegmen. Stridulatory vein short, curved at the left side end, with about 30 teeth, two distinctly enlarged in the middle. Teeth distance subequal except for the two enlarged in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[464,554,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Cu2 vein of left tegmen curved and slender, spectrum slender and rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[160,250,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Ninth abdominal tergite with notch V-shaped; 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[831,844,186,200]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">th</superScript>
abdominal tergite with a shallow notch. Supra-anal plate triangular with medium groove at base. Cercus robust at base, inner middle with a slight projection; apical third finger-shaped and curved inwards; apex acute, slightly curved downward (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1125,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate long with a medium longitudinal groove, lateral ridge well developed, posterior margin with a rounded excision; styli long and slender, almost as long as subgenital plate (
<figureCitation box="[636,721,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
