<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1401,1968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1401,1427]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Female</emphasis>
: Pronotum dorsally flat; tegmina reaching tip of meta femora, slightly suppassing or not reaching tip of ovipositor. Cerci conical, apex acute, slightly curved inward (
<figureCitation box="[898,992,1437,1463]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate wide, triangle, apex rounded, slightly concave. Ovipositor dagger shaped, nearly straight and robust, slightly decurved at base, apex acute (
<figureCitation box="[226,316,1509,1535]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[154,1433,381,1200]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological features of Hexacentrus formosanus sp. nov. A) male head and pronotum in lateral view B) same in dorsal view C) male stridulatory area in dorsal view D) male stridulatory file of left tegmina in ventral view E) apex of male abdomen and cerci in dorsal view F) male subgenital plate in ventral view G) female superanal plate and cerci in dorsal view H) female ovipositor in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556700/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1401,1968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1545,1571]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Coloration</emphasis>
: Overall green when alive. Antennal scape pink or yellow. Dorsal band brown with dark brown and yellow margin. Female dorsal part of tegmina dark brown. Tibia color variable from pink to greenish yellow (Fig. 4,5). Base of tibia spines, pretarsus and apical tarsal pads dark brown in both sexes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1401,1968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,258,1653,1679]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Song</emphasis>
: Songs include two parts. The first part includes continually pulses without interval. The second part repeats with 12â€“13 cycles in one minute. It contains 1.635Â± 
<geoCoordinate box="[830,904,1689,1716]" degrees="0.343" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="550" precision="55" value="-0.343">0.343s</geoCoordinate>
duration with first half loud and 3.158Â± 
<geoCoordinate box="[1363,1436,1689,1716]" degrees="0.358" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="550" precision="55" value="-0.358">0.358s</geoCoordinate>
interval, but duration gradually decreased in the whole song.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1401,1968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1761,1787]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Comparison</emphasis>
: This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wang &amp; Shi, 2005" authorityName="Wang &amp; Shi" authorityYear="2005" box="[668,1039,1761,1788]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hexacentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="expansus">
<emphasis box="[668,809,1762,1787]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">H. expansus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, J. - F. &amp; Shi, F. - M." box="[820,1039,1761,1788]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550" pagination="242 - 246" refId="ref5918" refString="Wang, J. - F., Shi, F. - M. (2005) A taxonomic review of the genus Hexacenthrus Serville from China (Orthoptera: Conocephalidae). Acta Entomologica Sinica, 48 (2), 242 - 246." type="journal article" year="2005">Wang &amp; Shi, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorochov &amp; Warchalowska-Sliwa, 1999" authorityName="Gorochov &amp; Warchalowska-Sliwa" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hexacentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inflatissimus">
<emphasis box="[1101,1281,1761,1787]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">H. inflatissimus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov, A. V. &amp; Warchalowska-Sliwa, E." pageId="7" pageNumber="550" pagination="265 - 269" refId="ref5236" refString="Gorochov, A. V. &amp; Warchalowska-Sliwa, E. (1999) A new species of the genus Hexacentrus (Orthoptera, Tettigoniidae) from Vietnam and its karyotypic features. Acta Zoologica Cracoviensia, 42, 265 - 269." type="journal article" year="1999">Gorochov &amp; Warchalowska-Sliwa, 1999</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the former species by 1) male file of left tegmina shorter; 2) spectrum of male left tegmina slender and rectangular; 3) male Cu2 vein of left tegmina curved and slender; and differs from the latter species by 1) body smaller; 2) female tegmina narrow and shorter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1401,1968]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,481,1905,1931]" pageId="7" pageNumber="550">Measurements (in mm)</emphasis>
